    "translations": {
      "en": {
        "summary": "Imam Musa al-Kazim (peace be upon him) responded to two divergent theological positions on God's nature — that of Hisham ibn Salim, who described God with some qualified anthropomorphism, and that of Hisham ibn al-Hakam, who explicitly said God is a body (jism). The Imam emphatically rejected all corporeal descriptions of God, citing the Quranic principle that nothing resembles Him, and condemned in the strongest terms the ascription of body, form, creaturely nature, limitation, or body parts to the Creator. This teaching situates al-Kazim within the Imami theological tradition of transcendent divine unity, which regards corporeal anthropomorphism as not merely mistaken but as a grave moral and religious offense.",
        "key_terms": {
          "جسم": "Body, corporeal substance — the term used by Hisham ibn al-Hakam to describe God, rejected by the Imam",
          "فحش": "Obscenity, abomination — a term for gross indecency, here applied to anthropomorphic theology",
          "خنا": "Turpitude, treachery, baseness — used alongside fuhsh to describe the moral gravity of anthropomorphism",
          "تحديد": "Limitation, delimitation — ascribing finite boundaries to God",
          "أعضاء": "Body parts, limbs — physical members, whose attribution to God is rejected",
          "عُلُوًّا كَبِيرًا": "A great elevation — Quranic phrase (17:43) affirming God's absolute transcendence"
        },
        "seo_question": "What did Imam al-Kazim say about describing God as having a body?"
      },
      "ur": {
        "summary": "امام موسیٰ الکاظم علیہ السلام نے دو متضاد عقیدوں کا جواب دیا — ہشام بن سالم اور ہشام بن الحکم کے۔ آپ نے اللہ کو جسم یا صورت یا محدود ذات قرار دینے کو شدید الفاظ میں رد کرتے ہوئے فرمایا کہ ایسا عقیدہ بدترین فحش اور بدکاری ہے۔",
        "key_terms": {
          "جسم": "جسم — اللہ کو جسمانی ذات ماننا، جسے امام نے رد کیا",
          "فحش": "فحش — بدترین برائی، یہاں تجسیم کے لیے استعمال",
